Jaguars silence Mustangs in Cesafi Vball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars shut down the Cebu Roosevelt Memorial Colleges (CRMC) Mustangs, 3-0, in the Cesafi 23 Men’s Volleyball game at the University of Southern Philippines Foundation (USPF) Gymnasium on Sunday, November 12.

The USJ-R Jaguars consistently maintained an edge against the CRMC Mustangs in three sets, leaving them with scores of 25-15, 9-25, and 25-17.

Jaguars’ Head Coach Roldan Potot commented on the team's performance against the newcomers.

“Wala silay ingon nga kaba, kay ilang kontra, bag-o lang naporma nga team ba,” he said.

Meanwhile, Potot reiterated what could be improved after the Jaguars’ win against the Cebu Institute of Technology-University (CIT-U) Wildcats (3-1) on Saturday, November 11.

“Akong [ingon] nila nga ang service namo, i-improve [pa] gyod. Blocking, ‘nya ug first touch, mahatod [gyod] sa [kontra]. Nindot na ang dagan sa atong team this time,” he said.

Moreover, he addressed the habit of the players on becoming complacent after securing a comfortable lead.

“Ako lang gyod giingnan sila nga ‘duwa lang mo sa inyong game, dili lang gyod mo advance og panghuna-huna.’ One step at a time,” Potot added.

The Jaguars will face the Felipe R. Verallo (FRV) College Blue Dragons on November 25 at the same venue.

via Juan Enrique Reboquio | FORWARD Staff Writer

Photos Courtesy: Erico Blaza | Jaguars Volleyball Player

ICYMI: The curtains have closed on the highly anticipated PolSci Days 2023 at the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Basak Campus on November 11.

First-year Political Science students, collectively known as BIDLISIW, were named the overall champion at the two-day event featuring a variety of games, sports, and competitions.

Here is the rundown of the events and their corresponding team placements:

Badminton
Champions: HIRAYA
1st Runner-Up: BIDLISIW
2nd Runner-Up: DILAAB
3rd Runner-Up: HAGAWHAW

Volleyball
Champions: DILAAB
1st Runner-Up: HAGAWHAW
2nd Runner -Up: HIRAYA
3rd Runner-Up: BIDLISIW

Basketball (Men)
Champions: HIRAYA
1st Runner-Up: BIDLISIW
2nd Runner-Up: DILAAB
3rd Runner-Up: HAGAWHAW

Basketball (Women)
Champions: HAGAWHAW
1st Runner-Up: BIDLISIW
2nd Runner-Up: HIRAYA

Extemporaneous Speech
Champions: HAGAWHAW
1st Runner-Up: DILAAB
2nd Runner-Up: BIDLISIW
3rd Runner-Up: HIRAYA

Oration
Champions: HIRAYA
1st Runner-Up: HAGAWHAW
2nd Runner-Up: DILAAB
3rd Runner-Up: BIDLISIW

Mr. & Ms. PolSci 2023
Mr. PolSci 2023 - Alfrancis Gregi Gillera from HIRAYA
Ms. PolSci 2023 - Edna Mae Quimat from BIDLISIW

Batch BIDLISIW comprises the first-year students, HIRAYA represents the second-year students, DILAAB encompasses the third-year students, and HAGAWHAW designates the fourth-year students, all enrolled in the Bachelor of Arts in Political Science program at USJ-R.

Jaguars take second draw against Warriors in Cesafi Fball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars had their second draw in the Cesafi 23 Football match against the University of San Carlos (USC) Warriors on Sunday, November 12, at USC Talamban Campus.

In the game’s first half, both teams struggled to take the lead despite multiple goal attempts.

Meanwhile, pressure was visible on the Jaguars’ line of defense during the second half, as the Warriors continuously returned the ball on their side of the field and narrowed their goal-kick chances.

Jaguars’ Head Coach Joselito Bono showed frustration as the team lagged behind and missed opportunities at the sidelines.

Moreover, Jaguars Team Captain and Goal Keeper Eugenn De Arce expressed his sentiments on the team’s losing effort to securing a goal.

“Nindot man ang among dula, nindot among performance. But in the end, wala na-convert among chances ba. So next game, mao na ang need buhaton sa team,” he said.

De Arce also commended the efforts of the team in facing the Warriors’ wrath on the field.

“Knowing USC, ilang style of play kay ing-ana man, pasa-pasa. I commend the [team] kay na defend gihapon nila for how many minutes. I appreciate the composure,” he added.

The Jaguars will meet the USC Warriors again in their next football match on November 18, at 1 p.m. and at the same venue.

via Sharry Cuizon | FORWARD Probationary Writer

[JOSENIANS MOVING FORWARD]

The Calling and The Choice: Committing to the Unconventional
by Krisha Faye Gascon | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Deep within the reservoir of childhood dreams and starry-eyed aspirations, there’s one question that echoes through the years: “What do you want to be when you grow up?”

For most, these dreams fade into the background as life’s well-trodden paths beckon. But for a rare few, destiny weaves an unexpected calling, leading them through uncharted and extraordinary landscapes.

Such is the journey of Sister Maria Fe Hilacan, a remarkable 31-year-old nun, a dedicated junior sister within the embrace of the Franciscan Sisters pro Infante Et Familia (FSpIF) and a first-year Psychology student at the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R).

A Fateful High School Epiphany

In high school, Sister Maria Fe and her classmates embarked on the age-old tradition of discussing their future careers during a vacant period. Little did she know that she would inadvertently unveil her destiny.

“Sige, at the age of 29, if I’m settled and my family is okay, I'll enter the convent,'” she boldly declared out of the blue.

However, destiny had different plans. She joined the convent three years earlier than her initial projection, setting her on a unique and life-altering journey.

The Multifaceted Life

Just when you think Sister Maria Fe is only confined to the title of being a nun, she proves that she has lived a life of multiple layers.

Before answering the calling of the convent, Sister Maria Fe had already earned a degree in computer programming from the Datamex Institute of Computer Technology (DICT), thanks to the generous scholarship provided by the FSpIF.

Yet, even with her academic achievements, her high school curiosity still burned brightly.

“Actually, kani nga community is mao sad ang nag-support nako pag-college so former scholar ko nila. Then akong [paternal] auntie sad isa sa mga madre and then visiting niece ko didto sa community. So whenever I see mga sisters nga same sa iyaha, naa btaw energy na, ‘Uy, ganahan ko mag madre lagi.’ Ato na time nag huna-huna nako na basin naay possibility kay grounded man mi sa mga seminars, recollections, and activities sa community,” she shared.

Following graduation, she delved into the world of surplus cars from Japan, securing an office job. Her life seemed to be unfolding in the classic Filipino fashion, and she had checked off all the expected boxes.

However, a pivotal moment arrived when her family needed her support. Her maternal aunt in Manila had fallen ill with breast cancer, compelling Sister Maria Fe to resign from her job and become her dedicated caretaker. But she never thought that from that day onward, her life was on the cusp of another profound transformation.

The Unexpected Calling

While caring for her ill aunt in Manila, she received an unexpected call from her paternal aunt asking her to consider joining the convent.

“‘Nya niingon man ko nga, ‘Pwede unya na lang? Kay naa pa man ko diri [sa Manila],’” she conveyed.

Sister Maria Fe hesitated, considering delaying her decision. However, fate intervened, and she found herself agreeing to do a search at the convent in Cebu.

Upon arrival, she was one of three candidates. But as time passed, she emerged as the solitary individual embarking on her journey within the convent.

A Life Redefined

Although she had already experienced life beyond the average, the commitment to her personal transformational journey proved to be a challenging endeavor.

Letting go of the life she had known for 26 years that laid the foundation for who she is now was challenging for Sister Maria Fe.

“[Being away from my family was] lisod kaayo oy. [There were moments] na moingon ko, ‘Sister, can I go home and visit Mama and Papa?’ [There was a lot of back and forth] until gipangutana ko nila na sure na ba jud ko,” she expressed.

As the youngest in her family and the unica hija, her mother initially had a difficult time accepting her choice, unlike her father and her older brothers, who accepted her decision promptly. However, over time, her mother eventually came to respect her firm decision.

“I’m thankful sad na ang community kay supportive. Na-anad man gud ko nga kung asa ko molakaw naa ako family. Ila ko gi-hinay-hinay na kana btaw’ng pwede ko mouli [karon] but the next day dili na sad ko pwede mouli. Hangtod sa isa ka-week kausa na lang ko mouli and hangtod sa naabot na karon every day na ko sa convent mouli,” she recounted.

Education and Formation

After entering the convent, Sister Maria Fe ventured to Manila for her religious formation. But her journey of learning was far from over. At the advice of her fellow sisters, she pursued religious studies at the Institute of Formation and Religious Studies (IFRS).

However, her educational journey faced a halt during the pandemic when she was required to return to Cebu after three years, leaving her one year short of her religious studies degree.

A New Calling: Psychology

Intriguingly, her journey took yet another twist. Her superior general suggested that she pursue a degree in Psychology at USJ-R. While Sister Maria Fe had not initially desired this path, the reason was compelling.

The convent needed a psychologist, especially for family-related services, aligning with their community mission. It was an essential role that Sister Maria Fe, being the youngest in the community, was encouraged to undertake.

Bridging Worlds

Starting a new chapter at 31 among teenagers was a unique challenge for Sister Maria Fe. She felt like a fish out of water but stood committed to her path.

“First few months lisod kaayo no kay lahi na sad nga environment, especially na akong mga [kuyog] kay under 19s, 20s, wala gyuy maabot og 30s, ako ra. So at first I was like, ‘Woah ako ra may kinamagulangan,’ pero I stand [committed] na ka-level ra ko nila ba. I have to wake up early in the morning pa and I have to manage my time jud–as part of being a nun,” she explained.

Sister Maria Fe’s journey is not just about self-discovery; it’s about finding new ways to serve her community. Her faith remains the core of her being, but the knowledge she gains as a Psychology major enhances her ability to support those in need.

“I learned to love psychology even if pag-first naka-ingon ko na, ‘Struggle na sad ni kay laing course.’ Pero para nako, dako kaayo siya na impact kay mag-meet man together ang science og ang faith in getting to know an individual, their attitude and their character,” she shared.

Despite the weight on her shoulders, Sister Maria Fe remains steadfast and optimistic in her approach.

“Naa jud koy [principle] sa akong self na positive lang whatever the outcome [is] kay gisulti sa akong mga sisters is if ever maglisod ko I would just tap their shoulder and initiate lang jud ko and dili ko angay ma-worry. Ang naka-nindot kay naa koy support system,” she added.

Serving a Higher Purpose

For Sister Maria Fe, her role in the community is to be at the service of her brothers and sisters in Christ, especially those at risk, endangered, and deprived children and families.

“I am now pursuing this degree program not just for my benefit but because of the need of my community, the FSpIF apostolate, and ministry,” she said.

In an era often marked by indecision and lack of commitment, Sister Maria Fe’s story serves as a testament to the power of faith, determination, and selflessness in adding layers to one’s soul. Her path, though unconventional, embodies the pursuit of a greater good, encouraging us all to consider our own unique callings in life.

Visuals by Heron Augustus Flores | FORWARD Probationary Artist

#OnTheGo

Jaguars triumph against Cheetahs in Cesafi Basketball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars secured a hard-fought victory over the Benedicto College (BC) Cheetahs, 55-51, in the Cesafi 23 Men’s Basketball game on Sunday, November 12, at the Cebu Coliseum.

The USJ-R Jaguars faced a challenging start due to a barrage of fouls that disrupted their rhythm.

Despite struggling to find their pace, the Jaguars scored their first point in the opening quarter with only three minutes left on the game clock.

In the last minutes of the first quarter, Jaguars’ Rhustin Rodriguez suffered a minor eye injury, concluding with the Cheetahs gaining the upper hand, 8-16.

However, the Jaguars rallied back in the second quarter, thanks to the efforts of Jake Engbino, Klein Chievin Gordillo, Aaron Tabio, and Elmer Echavez.

They propelled the team forward by closing the gap and ending the second period at 28-24.

Jaguars’ Point Guard and Shooting Guard Jay Deiparine stood out in the second half, exhibiting swift moves and a scoring spree, despite both teams missing several turnovers during the third quarter, 38-38.

The Jaguars then maintained their momentum until the fourth quarter, eventually resulting in their victory.

Meanwhile, Jaguars’ Head Coach Melo Banua remained positive despite the tight victory.

“Mura mi og nakalusot sa butas ng karayom, but I am always positive. There is no perfect basketball [game]. I just stayed positive nga makabawi ra ang team,” he said.

Moreover, Deiparine, who was named star player of the game, attributed their win to the collective efforts of the team.

“Medyo crucial jod ang game today, but we focused more sa defense,” he said.

“Teamwork gyod ang nagpadaog namo karon, walay kanya-kanya. Wala ko ga-expect nga ma-best player karon, kay I was doing it for the whole team,” he added.

The Jaguars will be facing the University of Southern Philippine Foundation (USPF) Panthers on Saturday, November 18, at 5 p.m. and at the same venue.

CRCESI conducts handwashing, deworming initiative

The Center for Recollect Community Engagement and Social Involvement (CRCESI) from the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) held a ’Paglaum sa mga Bata sa Carbon’ program focusing on handwashing and deworming at the Main Lobby on November 11.

This outreach program was in collaboration with the University’s Biology Students’ Association (BioSA) and the University Health and Services Department.

CRCESI Director, Rev. Fr. Rouel Sia, OAR, reminded the children of the purpose and goal of the ’Paglaum sa mga Bata sa Carbon’ in his opening speech.

“Dumdomi nga [atong] aim diri, ang atong katuyuan [karon] kay para makatabang kami kaninyo, unta magmalumbuon ug magpadayon kini, welcome sa USJ-R og enjoy,” he said.

Moreover, the program proceeded with the Department of Mathematics and Sciences Professor, Dr. Julios Dequillo, in discussing the importance, effects, and essentiality of handwashing in children’s development and hygiene.

“In their age, if they have this practice already, mostly they will be able to train themselves and input this [knowledge] into their system as normal and will be practiced all throughout their lives [contributing] to the development of their personal hygiene,” he said.

A demonstration of the techniques on how to properly wash their hands was conducted by Dequillo and the USJ-R BioSA student officers with the selected children.

In an interview, USJ-R BioSA President Kyle Jero Dico acknowledged the presence of the faculty, officers, and student volunteers who attended the program, together with 55 out of 68 children in Carbon.

“I encourage every Josenian to participate in these outreach activities because it allows us to ground ourselves in the experiences of the people by interacting with them, enhancing our leadership skills and empathy [towards] others,” he added.

Furthermore, the children lined up for the deworming session with the Health and Services Department, followed by the distribution of handwashing kits.

DOT Region 7, THMD conduct FBSE seminar

The Department of Tourism (DOT) Regional Office 7 held a Filipino Brand of Service Excellence (FBSE) workshop in partnership with the University of San Jose-Recoletos Tourism and Hospitality Management Department (USJ-R THMD) at USJ-R Basak Campus Audio-Visual Room (AVR) on Saturday, November 11.

The program tackled the Filipinos’ hospitality through FBSE which is believed to be essential in making every aspect of tourism in carrying Filipino values.

FBSE envisioned its goals to standardize the positive traits of hospitality and service that can be portrayed by all domestic and international stakeholders to make the “Filipino tourism workforce ready for a changed world.”

Moreover, Environmental Planner Ruel Rigor Javier of DOT-Region 7 highlighted the importance of having the Filipino brand warmth from arrival to departure and “its pursuit to consistently meet and surpass the guests’ needs and provide them with a memorable and fun experience.”

Assistant Project Officer Riane Vicariel Sinadjan firmly believed that the students who attended the seminar are the “ambassadors of Filipino core values,” and the lessons they will learn will be carried out in their future endeavors.

“I believe madala ra jod ni nila anywhere they go. They are the representation of [hospitable] people and the future workforce of the [hospitable] industry,” she expressed.

Meanwhile, the Chairperson of the seminar, Diana Marie Lapas, shared her gratitude for the opportunity given as they were the first batch to experience the FBSE seminar and for the wisdom the event had instilled in them.

“We have the foundation na to be used sa among workforce and with that, we really do have the advantage nga we have the training in the field,” Lapas stated.

The second batch of the FBSE seminar-workshop will be held next Saturday, November 18.

The article has been updated at 3:30 p.m. to rectify the following mistakes: Sinadjan was referred to as the ”Assistant Project Officer” but now corrected to ”Tourism instructor.” It was also clarified that Javier is not associated with DOT-Region 7. USJ-R JPSS opens Polsci Days '23

The University of San Jose-Recoletos Josenian Political Science Society (USJ-R JPSS) kickstarted their Polsci Days 2023 at the USJ-R Main Lobby on Friday afternoon November 10.

With the theme, ”TINUGYANAY: ANG PAG PADAYON SA PAGLAMBO SA ATONG PANAGHIUSA” the event fosters student connections to enhance their academic journey.

Crisjer Cadampog, a Political Science professor, expressed his gratitude to the success of the program and intensified how the event is geared towards ”not merely an academic endeavor, but as a holistic experience that encompasses both academic and non-academic activities.”

”Political Science Days provide an opportunity for students to test their knowledge and engage in scholarly discourse and exchange ideas to deepen their understanding of Political Science,” Cadampog added.

Meanwhile, the President of JPSS, Trisha Acasio, shared how happy she is for the success of the opening program with Josenian alumni returning to witness this year's Polsci Days.

"Everything is put together even though daghan mi’g problems na face but at the same time we still managed to keep everyone present and to participate with the activities," she stated.

The two-day program will culminate with Mr. and Ms. Polsci at the USJ-R Basak Campus on Saturday afternoon, November 11.

Students will answer the assessment through their Student Information System (SIS) account under the ”Performance Evaluation” tab in the dashboard.

This initiative aims to enhance class management and lesson delivery, contributing to continuous quality improvement mechanisms.

From Zamboanga, with Love
by Louella Grace Eroma | Josenian Contributor

“Angel Grace, what do you want to be when you grow up?” I asked my sister while sitting in the chair in our garden.

“I want to be an architect one day, Kuya Aldee, and build a house for our parents,” she replied with a huge smile on her face.

My sister loves to draw buildings and houses, and she loves math too.

“What about you, Kuya Aldee, what is your dream?” she asked me.

“I want to become a lawyer one day and help the people who need legal advice and other legal assistance. And aside from that, I want to be the mayor of Zamboanga City,” I replied, smiling back at her.

“Wow, that‘s great, Kuya. It’s a long way to becoming the mayor of our city, especially since there are a lot of people fighting for that position. I hope and pray to God and Our Lady of the Pillar for you,” she said.

Yes, we are devotees of Our Lady of the Pillar, our patroness here in Zamboanga City.

Our mother called us for dinner and her voice could be heard outside.

“You go ahead, Angel Grace. I need to clean up the mess first,” I said to her before leaving.

Sometimes, being the eldest in the family is not easy. There are many responsibilities that you need to take care of, which can be tiring at times.

I went inside our house after cleaning and they were still eating. I sat down in a chair and got my food.

lAldee, Angel told me that you want to be mayor of Zamboanga City soon,” my mother said.

“Yes, Mama, I want to follow in my father’s footsteps,” I replied.

“Are you sure, Aldee? Being the mayor of Zamboanga City is not easy. You will deal with lots of paperwork, sign documents, and face the crowd,” my father said.

“But if that’s what you want, then I will support you,” Papa added.

“Muchísimas gracias (thank you), Papa,” I said and hugged him.

“Study well, Aldee,” he replied.

I have chosen to pursue a Bachelor of Arts in Political Science in college. This is the best degree program for me because I want to become a lawyer and study in Cebu City.

I decided to keep my decision to study in Cebu City a secret from my parents until after my graduation.

I know that it will be difficult to study in a city where I don’t speak its language, Cebuano. Our mother tongue here in Zamboanga City is Chavacano, a Spanish-based creole. This is why our city is also known as “Asia's Latin City.”

Dinner was over, and it was Angel Grace’s turn to wash the dishes while I prepared my things for school the next day to attend our graduation orientation.

While scrolling through my mother’s phone, I saw some announcements from our school and found out that I was the class valedictorian! I was surprised and delighted.

”Mom, Dad, look!” I exclaimed.

“Wow, Aldee, congratulations! You made it. We’re so proud of you,” my mother said. They were very happy with the news.

The next day, my mother woke me up and reminded me about the orientation.

I went straight to the bathroom while my mother cooked breakfast for me.

After taking a shower, I went to my bedroom to put on my uniform and eat my breakfast.

“Hurry up, Aldee! Your dad is waiting for you in the car!” my mom shouted from downstairs.

I was brushing my teeth at the time and in a hurry as well. I grabbed some of my things and went to the car.

As I made my way to school, I was met with a sea of students, all rushing to get to class. The crowd was so thick that I was nearly late. Luckily, I arrived safely after five minutes.

While walking to my classroom, I almost fell down the stairs.

Fortunately, Jahida, a Tausug girl who has been my confidante and best friend since grade school, saw me.

Jahida asked if I was alright, and I smiled in reply.

“Alhamdulillah, Aldee. I’m glad nothing bad happened to you,” she said.

I continued on my way to class.

Our class adviser was observing us and waiting for our principal.

“Class, please minimize your noise,” our adviser said. But no one was listening to her.

Our class adviser was furious, having repeatedly told us to quiet down.

“Please have discipline. You are now about to enter college life, but your behavior still looks like that of high school students. Please,” she said to us.

Then the principal came to our classroom and said, “What's all the commotion about here?” Everyone was silent.

The graduation orientation has begun, and the speakers are presenting their agenda and the details of our graduation ceremony.

“For the practice, we will start on Monday at one in the afternoon. Everyone must join the graduation practice, otherwise, you cannot attend the graduation ceremony. This is only one round of practice,” the principal said.

“And everyone must attend the baccalaureate mass, too. Attendance will be checked in there, as well as the distribution of the garlands,” she added.

Since we were already informed of what to do, we were dismissed early by the principal.

My mom decided to pick me up at our school since my dad couldn’t due to his heavy workload at the city hall.

We were going to the pueblo (town) to wait for my dad, since his work ends at 5 p.m.

“Mang kunambre io (Mom, I’m hungry),” I said.

“Io tamen kunambre ya noy (I’m hungry too, son),” she replied.

Our stomachs were growling, and we were hungry. So we headed to the mall in search of food, but the restaurants were packed and the prices were high. My mom suggested we go to Paseo del Mar instead.

My dad texted me that he was about to leave his office.

Sender: Dad

Aldee, please tell your mom that I’m almost done with my work here. I’ll go out at 5 p.m. and also please tell your mom that we’ll go to Pasonanca later on. Meet me at the entrance of the city hall. I love you.

Sent to: Aldee

“Mom, Dad texted me and said he’s almost out. We'll meet him at the city hall entrance,” I informed my mother.

“Okay, let him know we're on our way,” she replied.

Sender: Aldee

Dad, I just told Mom about this and she said we'll go there. We're now at Paseo del Mar eating. See you later, Dad.

Sent to: Dad

As I looked around the town, I smiled.

I really love my city, and I'm proud to be a Zamboangueño.

At five o’clock in the afternoon, we met up with my dad.

“Hello, Dad. How’s work?" I asked him.

“Very tiring, Aldee,” he replied.

“How's your orientation? Anyway, congratulations in advance for making it, and for moving on to your next journey.” He said and hugged me.

My dad seemed to be struggling to say something to me.

“What is it, Dad?” I asked.

He couldn't hide it anymore.

“Anak, your mom and I have decided to send you to Cebu City to study. We know it's your dream.”

Wait, what? How did he know? I haven’t even told them about it yet, but I’m very happy. I put a huge smile on my face and jumped with joy.

“Really, Dad? For real?” I still couldn’t believe it was true.

“Yes, anak, it‘s true. You deserve it,” Mom said.

I hugged both of them and thanked them.

“Thank you so much, Mom and Dad. I promise I’ll do my best in Cebu City for college.”

“You’re welcome, our future mayor of Zamboanga City. Do well with your studies,” Dad replied.

I hugged them again with a big smile on my face.

Yari Kapag ‘Di Sinunod: Filipino Superstitions and Urban Legends That You Should Know
by Rufino Rico Jamisola | FORWARD Staff Writer & Aliyaah Alvez | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Superstitions and urban legends have always had their way with Filipinos, with their rich history passed down from generation to generation.

A blend of indigenous to Spanish influences, from various beliefs on avoiding sweeping at night to using salt to ward off evil spirits, has painted the Filipino tapestry in a color of cultures.

What happens when these rules are not followed? Well, it’s easy to guess: the consequences will follow you like crazy.

So, are you ready to deal with these superstitions? Stick around as we’ll uncover more captivating beliefs that roam around this Halloween season together.

Visayas Art Fair 2023, Bodega Caravan holds a press conference

The Visayas Art Fair (VAF) and Bodega Caravan’s four-day event commenced with a press conference at Horizons Cafe, Oakridge Business Park, on Thursday, November 9.

The Chairwoman of Cebu Design Week (CDW), Maria Luisa Booth, shared the core themes of art, culture, and design.

”In the past five years, we have opened art fairs, celebrating culture, promoting design, as we had trained shows, designed awards, and collaborated with the three segments: art, design, and culture communities of Cebu,” she said.

Booth also shared her team’s vision of renewing their brand through signature events that are soon to be announced on social media and web platforms.

Following Booth’s remarks, Laurie Boquiren, Chairwoman of VAF, announced the event will have 14 exhibitors from the Visayas, 12 from the National Capital Region (NCR), one from Mindanao, and two international participants from Korea.

“From the very first time, the Luzon Art Fair, the Visayas Art Fair, [and] Mindanao Art Fair—all of these three major art events will converge here in Cebu for the Visayas Art Fair,” she said.

Boquiren added that the three major art fairs are recognized by the National Commission for Culture and Arts (NCCA).

Moreover, the VAF is set to feature art installations along with the illumination event of a 25-foot crotched Christmas tree.

The President of CDW, Christina Gaston, explained that the inspiration for Bodega Caravan stems from the nostalgic allure of traditional traveling wood carts.

”From traditional traveling wood carts that would come to the cities from the province to show and sell to us that’s really where we got the name ‘Bodega Caravan,’” Gaston stated.

The last speaker for the conference, Gil Zaire ‘Butch’ Carungay, the Design Director and Cebu UNESCO City of Design Commissioner, Cebu City Tourism Commission, introduced the Blue Mangoes Award (BMA) as a platform to recognize and reward creativity across various disciplines.

”Entries are currently being accepted from designers and creative entrepreneurs not just in Cebu, but also within Region VI, VII, and VIII,” Carungay said.

Furthermore, Kenneth Cobonpue, a multi-awarded Filipino furniture designer and the Curator of Bodega Design Caravan, will be the speaker for VAF.

The VAF and Bodega Caravan will start on November 23 exclusively for VIPs, while the Bodega Caravan’s sales will begin on November 25.

The event will be open to the general public from 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. on November 24–26 at Oakridge Business Park.

We are three days away before we hold our groundbreaking ceremony. We are inviting our alumni in Ormoc to witness this milestone at Barangay Bantigue. You may send a message to the USJ-R Alumni Association Inc. to confirm your attendance.
